# Loading the data
loan_tape_data <- read_excel("Loan Tape Review.xlsx")



Preparing the Data for Analysis

# Using `janitor` package to turn all column names into lower case (this facilitates the analysis)
loan_tape_data <- loan_tape_data %>% clean_names()

# Removing typo where year is 2028
loan_tape_data <- loan_tape_data[!(loan_tape_data$loan_id == "102096"),]

# Removing $500,000 loan outlier
loan_tape_data <- loan_tape_data[!(loan_tape_data$loan_amount == 500000),]

# creating a column `issue_year`
loan_tape_data <- loan_tape_data %>%
                  mutate(issue_year = year(issue_date))

# Creating `month` column to investigate any possible calendar effects in the data.
loan_tape_data <- loan_tape_data %>%
                  mutate( issue_month = zoo::as.yearmon(issue_date))
loan_tape_data$issue_month <- as.Date(loan_tape_data$issue_month)

# Turning `guarantee` into Indicator (Dummy) Variable
loan_tape_data$guarantee <- ifelse(loan_tape_data$guarantee == "Yes", 1, 0)

# Turning `loan_status` into indicator variable
loan_tape_data$loan_status <- ifelse(loan_tape_data$loan_status == "Repaid", 1, 0)



Summarizing the different types of loans they originate. (i.e.loan characteristics by cohorts)


This table represents average data points based on Credit Scores ranges.


# Summarizing data amount by credit score
mean_data_by_crd_score <- loan_tape_data %>% 
                            mutate(score_range = cut(credit_score, c(400, 500, 600, 700, 800, 900))) %>%
                            group_by(score_range) %>%
                            summarize(average_loan_amount = mean(loan_amount),
                                      average_interest = mean(interest_rate),
                                      average_loan_to_value = mean(loan_to_value),
                                      pctg_collateral_needed = sum(guarantee)/length(guarantee),
                                      pctg_repaid = sum(loan_status) / length(loan_status),
                                      total_loans = length(loan_id))

What factors appear to drive loan performance (repaid vs.defaulted)?

When regressing loan_status on credit_score, the coefficient on credit_score is statistically significant.

In other words, it seems to be the case that an individuals credit_score can be a good indicator as to whether or not they will repay the loan. The same applies to credit_rating, as seen in the output below.

Any concerns about the quality of the data? Any individual loans that warrant additional discussion with the originator?


Yes, I have found two outliers in this dataset.

(1) One of the loans had a corresponding amount of $500K; this value is significantly larger than all other loans. Moreover, although the corresponding credit score is relatively high (at 714), no collateral was asked. This makes me concerned about that quality of that specific observation in the dataset.

(2) Additionally, one of the loans (with id 102096) had an issue date of 2028. This was clearly a typo.



Final Thoughts

(i) Credit Scores:

Based on Table 1, the company tends to provide larger loans to people that have lower credit scores. Nonetheless, the interest that is charged on those loans is also higher for individuals with low scores.

When it comes to the loan_to_ratio variable, it is directly related to credit scores. That is to say that loan_to_ratio tends to be higher for individuals with high credit scores.

The percentage of loans repaid is directly correlated with credit scores (Fig. 5). In other words, individuals with high credit scores are more likely to repay their loans..

Lastly, loans granted to individuals with high credit scores are less likely to need collaterals as part of the process (Fig 6).


(ii) Credit Ratings:

From Table 2, only one of the loans was granted to a business with a 'D'-Credit Rating; that loan was not repaid.

Additionally, most loans were granted to businesses with a B-Rating. Companies with Ratings of A, B, C, D received respectively 1178, 2010, 787, and 1 loans.

Table 2 also highlights the fact that: interest is higher for low-rated companies, loan_to_value is higher for high-rated companies, high-rated companies are less likely to default (Fig. 7), and low-rated companies are more likely to need a collateral (Fig. 8).


(iii) Time Series:

Overall, Interest Rates have remained constant over time, in between 12 and 14 percent (as seen in Fig. 2) .

Loan_to_values have also remained constant over time, in between 80 and 85 percent (as seen in Fig. 3).

Whether a collateral was required has also remained constant over time (slightly higher in 2016); It has been between 40 and 50 percent (as seen in Fig. 4).

Loans issued in 2017-2018 were the most generous, as seen in Table 3 and Fig 1

Lastly, loans issues in 2020 were significantly less likely to be repaid. This can be seen in Table 3 and Fig. 9.


(iv) Seasonal Effects:**

When it comes to interest charged, there were no seasonal effects (as seen in Fig. 10).

When it comes to loan amounts, there are also no consistent patterns in the data - although it had a peak in Aug-Dec 2017 (Fig. 11).

Finally, there is a clear seasonanl pattern in the number of loans being issued. This company was much more likely to issue loans during June through October. This can be seen clearly in Figure 1.
